EQUINE INFECTIOUS ANEMIA - SWITZERLAND: (AARGAU), FIRST CASE
************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sun 10 Jul 2017
Source: Aargauer Zeitung (AZ) [German, mach-transl, summarised, edited]
https://www.aargauerzeitung.ch/aargau/kanton-aargau/toedliche-krankheit-fuer-pferde-birrfeld-wird-voruebergehend-zum-sperrgebiet-131511204


A case of Equine Infectious Anemia (EIA) has been diagnosed in M端lligen, canton Aargau; this is the 1st case of EIA in Switzerland since 1991. EIA is notifiable for horses and other solipeds like donkeys and mules. The cantonal veterinary service has declared the Birrfeld area as a restricted zone for the said. The disease does not affect humans and other animal species.

So far, there is no evidence that the disease has spread beyond M端lligen.

Infected animals, such as the one in M端lligen, must be killed. The remaining horses kept in the stable are placed under quarantine and should be strictly watched as required by the cantonal veterinary service.

The disease is transmitted by arthropods; all horses and other solipeds kept in the restricted area may be left in the open if they have been previously protected by effective insecticides.

According to the Animal Disease Regulation, a restricted area of one km [approx. 0.62 miles] around the contaminated horse farm should be implemented. Therefore, the cantonal veterinary service has declared the entire Birrfeld area to the restricted area [map included; see source url].

Within the said zone, all trade and traffic with horses is prohibited for 90 days. Horses and other solipeds should enter or leave the restricted area only with the written authorization of the cantonal veterinary service. Exhibitions, tournaments and similar events are prohibited in the restricted area until the cantonal veterinary service repeals the restricted area; presumably, after expiry of the statutory period of 90 days.

Not affected by the measure is the transport of horses across the highway.

