[Switzerland has become the 3rd European country involved in the EIA event which reportedly started in Germany on 2 Jan 2017 and in the Netherlands on 28 Jun 2017.

According to the following update of the transboundary event (summarized), published by the German web-site "wir-sind-vet" ("we are vets"), so far 15 horses have been officially confirmed as EIA-infected, of which 13 in Germany, one in the Netherlands and one in Switzerland. Most if not all the involved animals are polo horses; M端lligen is located in the Canton of Aargau, home to one of the 10 Swiss poloclubs. Officially the reference to the polo sport is not confirmed, but the restricted area includes the address of the club. No evidence for direct connection between the Dutch case and Germany could be found so far; the horse from the Poloclub Vreeland (Utrecht / 63 horses) was never in Germany according to Bob Rademakers, secretary of the Dutch polo association. According to the daily Bildzeitung, the horses infected in Hamburg were all from the same stable in Argentina and came to Germany 5 years ago. Even horses tested positive in other countries would come from that Argentine barn. This has been confirmed by a spokesman for the Altona district in Hamburg.

According to "wir-sind-vet", the Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut (FLI - National Reference Laboratory for EIA) has also confirmed the connection with the polo sport. The track to Argentina, however, is not officially communicated by the FLI. The above and additional information, including a map of the German locations where positive horses have been detected, is available at http://www.wir-sind-tierarzt.de/2017/07/equine-infektioese-anaemie-ausbrueche/. (Thanks to communicator SZ for providing the link).

Some of the above cited data are still in need of authoritative confirmation.

Subscribers are reminded about the lifelong, persisting infection in EIA-affected horses, which could be subclinical; hence, the term "outbreak" should not be regarded always as indicative of a new, fresh EIA case. Though apparently a "rolling event", detection of new cases/affected countries does not necessarily reflect a sequential order of infection. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5164560,2040.]
